column1996:
You're closer than you think

…but doubt doesn't know that.

Here's what happens right before the breakthrough:

→ You feel like nothing's working
→ You question if you're on the right path
→ You wonder if you should just quit

That's not a sign you're failing.

That's the exact moment most people walk away.

Right before:

→ The client says yes
→ The algorithm picks you up
→ The opportunity you didn't see coming finds you

The gap between "nothing's happening" and "everything's changing" is smaller than you think.

But here's the thing no one talks about:

Progress doesn't announce itself.

It builds quietly in the background while you're busy doubting yourself.

The email gets opened. The post gets shared. The referral gets made.

You just don't see it yet.

So if you're in the middle of the messy season:

The one where effort feels invisible and results feel distant.

Keep going.

Because quitting guarantees you'll never know how close you were.

There is a seat waiting for you at tables you didn't even know existed.

Trust the process.

Even when - especially when - you can't see the outcome yet.

Found this valuable? Please reshare with your network! ♻️

And follow Noemi Kis✨ for daily growth tips!

column1996:
Brothers. Since Day One.
Some friendships fade. Some friendships stretch across decades, deployments, life, loss, and every version of who we’ve become.
These two didn’t just step up to the line — they walked right over it.
Staff Sergeant Jason Richards, USMC
 Corporal Jed Richards, USMC
We grew up together. We got in trouble together. We figured life out the hard way. And they put on the uniform and carried a weight most people will never understand.

Wendy Harris (can you make sure they both see this...going to be like hearding cats. Godspeed). 
First memory of Jed: 3 years old, in a diaper, running laps around a basketball goal like it was the Indy 500.
Not much has changed — still too small to play and still wearing diapers, just a different brand (according to him).

Jason — the quiet one until the moment it mattered. The one who runs toward the fire when everyone else steps back. Never had to say much — because he showed up.

I didn’t serve. They did.

But I learned from them — loyalty, accountability, and doing hard things without needing applause for it.

Now your turn.

Who in the service are you personally thankful for?
Before anyone gets dramatic:
Yes — we honor all veterans and active service members.

But today is about the individuals who shaped your life.
Drop a name. Tell a story. Let them be seen while they’re still here to hear it.

Boomband need to borrow a speaker today. I'll give it back, someday. Maybe. Probably not. 

https://lnkd.in/g5jTeUku

Show them you LOVE life. 👏 👊 

Tony B.
#GRIND
Never. Forget. Where. Home. Is.💜

Tim, this is a dangerous statement.  God said many things to us in His Word, where we are greatly valued, loved, cherished, protected, covered, thought of, and beautifully and wonderfully made. But not once in His Word did He say WE are ENOUGH.

HE is ENOUGH. He is our Portion, our Rock, our Mighty Fortress, our Creator, our Comforter, our Judge, our Healer, our Sanctifier, our King, and our Greatest Love, the Lover of our souls. 

When we think WE are enough, we dive deeply into that space where we determine we don't have to change, turn from our wicked ways, rely solely on Him.

The Bible says in Jer 17:9, the heart is deceitfully wicked; who can know it?  If this is true, how are we possibly enough?  Romans 3:23 says ALL have sinned and have fallen short of the glory of God.  Do we believe God, Who is perfect, all-powerful, all-knowing, and most of all PERFECT LOVE?

WE are not enough, but HE absolutely is!

Feeling called to make a difference in Grand Forks, ND, I am excited to announce my vision for opening a safe bed with services designed to help families build a strong foundation and become productive members of our community once again.
This calling has been a long time in the making, as God has placed people in my life to guide me toward this mission. Our future, especially our youth, is at the heart of this endeavor.
I have developed three business plans for three houses to start in Grand Forks, ND:
1. A psychiatric and emotional disturbance treatment residential facility.
2. A program for young adults aged 18 to 26 who have aged out of foster care, focusing on life skills to prevent homelessness.
3. A hospitality house for families with children in the residential treatment facility, providing a space for visits and family therapy.
I believe that God is orchestrating this in His divine timing. The ripple effect of changing one life can impact many, and when we touch one life, we touch countless others. I am grateful for the resources provided along this journey, knowing that God is always our source. Together, we can bless the souls that come together to uplift others for His kingdom. column1988:
IT WAS A GOOD DAY.
AUGUST 11, 1973.
#HIPHOP50

I grew up on Hip-Hop. The Culture is in my heart and soul. It's in my DNA. It shaped my life. It showed me my purpose. It made me who I am. IYKYK. I REALLY LIVE THIS. These are just some of the people who inspired me from childhood, through college, to this day.

I come from a bloodline of poets and storytellers. Hip-Hop was how I was gonna carry on their legacy. They told me to keep going with it. As a second generation immigrant, some people didn't get it though, and thought I was chasing a dream. And you know what? THEY WERE RIGHT. Because isn't that what we're supposed to do? Go after our dreams? 

My Grandma told me "Reach out, aim high. No limits, as far as the sky. Along the way, there'll be hurdles to leap. Be surprised if the way gets smooth not steep." She never lied. I got her words tatted on my arm. Don't let those hurdles stop you, y'all. Hop over those hurdles, and KEEP GOING. 

Look, sometimes shit don't go the way we planned it. But don't panic. Breathe a minute. Sometimes the plan can turn to your purpose with just a pivot. So keep grindin, until you shining. Sometimes YOU GOTTA REMIND 'EM. 

And watch the dream become real. Sometimes it won't happen the way you thought it would. But, you know what? WE HERE NOW. 

And to me, that's what Hip-Hop always represented - the culture, the hustle, the grind, the hope, the community - we'll get there together. THANK YOU, HIP-HOP. 

"You never thought that Hip-Hop would take it this far." -B.I.G. 

#HIPHOP
#CULTURE

column853:
The grass isn’t always greener.  We see it all the time — companies or recruiters desperate to fill seats offering inflated guarantees to lure good employees away from great companies. On the surface, it feels like a win: a bigger paycheck, a shiny new opportunity, maybe even an ego boost.   But too often, once the guarantee runs out, reality sets in. Those “bad” things at the old company suddenly don’t look so bad anymore. The new company has fewer resources, less value to offer customers, and limited opportunities to succeed. That initial excitement fades into frustration as the employee realizes they can’t produce at the same level they once did — and their long-term earnings and satisfaction take a hit.
There’s usually a reason a company pays well above market to attract talent — it’s often to compensate for deeper issues.
Employees who chase these short-term gains tend to develop resumes filled with short stints — a pattern that becomes a red flag to future employers. Stability, loyalty, and a track record of consistent performance are worth far more in the long run than a temporary bump in pay.
The grass isn’t always greener — sometimes it’s just painted that way. 🌱

Its easy to spend someone else's money. Even as a VP in someone else's company, your budget is not YOUR money - its theirs. When you run your own business, you quickly realize that budgets are exhaustible and that business is sometimes not just quarter to quarter, but day to day.

Sometimes not being paid what others can or will pay an employee is NOT a sign of value, but affordability.  In other cases, I completely agree. But lets not paint every siutation with a broad stripe of assumption.

2. Having interviewed, hired, managed, developed, and released a countless number of employees over the last 30+ years in business (more than 1000, that I know), I can say that not every company, employer, manager, lead, is looking to replace you in six months just because you went with a better offer. Again with the broad brush...

column1996:
I watched a manager panic with a $100K counteroffer.
The sales rep was loyal for 6 years at $70K.
I said "But where's the $180k they underpaid you?"



This Sales Rep had been loyal for SIX YEARS.
 
Same $70K base salary. Territory shrinking every year. Quota going UP.

Then he found a new opportunity.
$100K base, bigger territory, similar commission.
When he resigned, his manager panicked:
“Wait, let me talk to HR and the executive team.”
Two days later: “We’ll match the $100K and give you more territory. We want to keep you.”

Here’s what I tell every candidate before they resign:
If they’re willing to pay you $30K more now,
Why didn’t they value you enough to pay it for the last six years?

Do the math, that’s $180K they underpaid you.
Where’s your retroactive bonus?

As a former VP of Talent Acquisition who managed 84 recruiters at a global company, I’ve seen this play out hundreds of times.

Companies that counter-offer are buying themselves six months to find your replacement.

Then they’ll remember you tried to quit.

I never once counter-offered. Here’s what I told departing employees:

 “You’re leaving for a reason. Let’s talk about how I can improve, but I want you to be successful in your new role.”

Because good leaders know the truth:

If you were truly valued, you wouldn’t be looking in the first place.

To employees considering counter-offers: it’s a slap in the face wrapped in false promises.

To hiring managers: if someone resigns, wish them well and learn from the feedback. Don’t play games with their career.

Trust is earned over years, not recovered with a panic raise.

column892:
The market has shifted—employers think they’re in the driver’s seat. I disagree: top talent still has options. The war for them is intensifying.
Key shifts I’ve seen:
Tighter candidate profiles → less flexibility
Wait for the “perfect” hire → risk aversion
AI hype vs. reality → Magnificent 7 execs tout AI-driven layoffs to boost stock. Example: Klarna replaced CS reps with AI, losses doubled, then  rehired humans and fires the AI chatbot.
Short-term gains, long-term pain—media laps up the drama.
This doesn’t help the average person paying bills or feeding a family. Companies are part of society. They have a responsibility to balance profit with social and economic stability.

As a dyslexic, I’ve noticed ChatGPT and Copilot often scramble meaning—classic dyslexic errors. If we’re replacing humans with AI, I’m deeply concerned. Humans built it. Humans make mistakes. AI does too.
AI does boost productivity it isan enabler, not a replacement. Let people do more with less, not nothing at all.
Seen it before: in the '90s, Xerox cut ~1,100 of 1,200 in Marlow (my dad kept his job). Within 12 months, they rehired 1,000.
Litmus test: If a company pitches its culture and values during the process, it actually values you.

🧂 🌊 Spotter Platform salinity sensors are available for pre-order now!

Salinity story time: In 4th grade science class, I learned about density. I was fascinated by density’s effect on the behavior of liquids, like how oil always floats to the top in a bottle of salad dressing. Around the same time, I learned about the Great Salt Lake. When I connected the dots that the salt dissolved in the lake increased the density of the water, and that’s why humans can float so well in the Great Salt Lake, it blew my 10-year-old mind. Inspired, I focused my science fair project on salinity and buoyancy: I placed plastic beads in a glass of tap water, where they immediately sank to the bottom. I then carefully added salt to the water, gram by gram, until, like magic, the beads floated to the top. When I learned about ocean circulation dynamics many years later, I immediately thought back to that simple experiment and the magical power of salinity.

Today, I have the immense privilege of working at Sofar Ocean with ocean scientists improving our ability to predict what’s happening in the ocean. By adding subsurface salinity sensors to our Spotter platform – co-located with surface winds, waves, SST, and pressure – we can better understand and forecast marine weather.

You can build your own Spotter configuration (including salinity) here: https://lnkd.in/e-jxk_dt

column1988:
Two VPs of Sales. Both took their company from $2M to $10M ARR in two years.

One did it with a $30M Series A: a full GTM team, strong RevOps, healthy budget.

The other did it with a $3.2M convertible note: a few SDRs, no marketing support, minimal capital to deploy.

Same ARR achievement. Very different operating environments.

If you are a founder / CEO hiring their first sales leader, that context matters.

Ask:
What level of resourcing have you operated with? 
How did the company perform against its stated growth goals / your sales forecast? 
How hands-on were you in building the GTM motion versus running it? What logos did you close personally?
Were you creating a new category or selling into an established one? 

So you can answer: 
Do they know how to win within our capital and market constraints?

Because the goal isn’t just to find a great leader, it’s to find the great leader who knows how to drive sustainable growth in an environment like yours.

Plot twist: They found me! 

After going completely off-grid in Northern Michigan (where the WiFi fears to tread) and decompressing in the Ozarks (yes, I DO unplug from LinkedIn occasionally), I emerged to discover Jeff Taylor and the Boomband team had me on their radar.

Here's what happens when you stop doom-scrolling job boards and start telling your ACTUAL story: 

Spoiler: No AI wrote my responses...Bigger spoiler: The mystery guest feedback was 🔥 ...Biggest spoiler: I'm ready to bring this energy to YOUR team  🥇 Flat out truth: Donna Star is the Yoda of Executive Coaches. I see you 😁 !

To my fellow job seekers: If I can survive explaining my career pivot while secretly hoping my hair looked decent on camera, YOU can put yourself out there too.

Hiring managers: Want someone who takes calculated risks (like appearing on podcasts) but also knows when to disconnect and recharge? Let's talk. I promise my interview skills are even better when I'm not worried about my WiFi cutting out from a cabin in the woods.

Thank you Jeff Taylor Madison Rose Keefer and the 'at one time' mystery guest Donna Star for creating a space where we can be gloriously, messily HUMAN in our job search!
Who else is tired of pretending their career path was a straight line? Its time, lets get it!

Tony B.

P.P.S. - the real win was getting to watch my son take the field in his freshman year of college football. #ProudDad #Grateful #Blessed
Jeff Taylor — guess that’s proof I’m exactly where I’m meant to be. I LOVE LIFE 👊 Boomband

column1996:
Exciting Day for TA Sales: We're hiring our Founding AE in Chicago 🤑 


WHY: 

We are on pace to double revenue for the second straight year primarily through referrals, inbound, and founder-led sales. Now we’re ready to build our outbound motion and need an A player to join the team. 

THE UPSIDE: 

For the right person, this is the opportunity of a lifetime: 

1. Get your Sales MBA by working day in and out with me and meet some of the best Sales Leaders in the world every single day. You will never have a boss more committed to your personal and professional growth. 

2. You're not just given a territory and quota: you'll be helping to build the GTM motion and propel us into $1M+ and beyond. 

3. We have an amazing team and make sales and training fun while we work on super ambitious goals! 

4. We are flooded with inbounds and referrals for you to capitalize on (in addition to going outbound). 

5. If you're entrepreneurial, learn what it's really like to build a business from scratch. 

THE DOWNSIDE: 

1. We have a small office in Chicago and believe in in-person/hybrid. Willing to make exceptions for the perfect candidate. 

2. We're a small and scrappy team with limited resources. If you need a lot of context and structure, this role may not be right for you. 

3. Selling to sales leaders is hard and humbling. You need to deal well with rejection. 

4. If you're not coachable, don't bother applying. I will boost you up but I will also be coaching the hell out of you every single day to be your very best. 

5. In addition to our inbound and referrals, we will need to get out of our comfort zone and continue to outbound using calls, emails, social and more. 


NEXT STEPS: 

1. Feel free to apply on LinkedIn if you're a great fit. 

2. Email me: tom(at)tasales(dot)co with SL: "Founding AE Application" or find a creative way to get ahold of me. 

3. Know someone? Tag 'em here. If we hire them, I will buy you and a +1 a fantastic dinner :). 


Let the games begin!

Today, I’m excited to share PepsiCo has agreed to acquire poppi, the fast-growing prebiotic soda brand. We’ve been evolving our food and beverage portfolio over many years at PepsiCo – whether we’re innovating with our iconic brands or making strategic acquisitions like Siete Family Foods and Sabra Dipping Company, we’re making sure we have even more positive choices for consumers. poppi will be a great complement to our portfolio as we continue to provide consumers with convenient and great-tasting options that fit their lifestyles and growing interest in health and wellness.

The transaction is subject to customary closing conditions, including regulatory approval.

column1996:
We figured it out!

We’ve successfully automated bill creation in NetSuite using Celigo—streamlining our process and unlocking valuable insights:

FedEx Bill -> FTP -> Celigo -> NetSuite

Each bill line automatically names a customer in NetSuite, allowing us to accurately measure Freight Out on a customer-by-customer basis. No more guesswork or hours of manual work!

We’ve expanded this to cover UPS and USPS bills as well, and we’re seeing massive improvements in visibility.

But that’s not all...this type of automated flow has broader applications. We’ve implemented it with our 3PL billing, enabling us to track Pick, Pack, and Ship costs by order and customer with precision.

The result? Better allocation of costs and clearer views of customer profitability. If you’re in the NetSuite space, there’s a ton of potential for flows like this to cut down manual entry and improve financial accuracy and decision making. 😊 

====
For those wondering: In an earlier post, I asked how folks were automating the allocation of detailed freight costs (FedEx, UPS) to sales orders/customers to improve profitability views. 

I’d love to hear more from anyone who’s using creative NetSuite automations thru workflows, scripting, or 3rd party integrations! 😊

I am obsessed with the launch of the $125 million supplement brand EHPlabs! Check the impact.

When we first met last year, they were drowning in over 20,000 support tickets per month.

30-45% of their ticket demand was customers making mistakes at checkout.

Customers can now edit orders self-service, so Cherie J. will never receive a support ticket again — all thanks to Order Editing.

Talk about making an impact 👊

Kiril Climson and I have loved working with Brendan Ridge and Matt Paterson to get this live - the energy is electric.

People say it's clear that I love the product that we've built. How could you not when you look at the problem we solve?

We've just improved tens of thousands of customers' lives, lifted operational hygiene and order accuracy, and made a customer service department's life 30% easier.

It's a privilege to be a part of such a carefully curated stack too! Shout out to:

Klaviyo and James White for powering Order Editing notification emails.

Tapcart and Neal Goyal for powering push notifications to customers' phones with last-chance offers to increase AOV.

Gorgias for crushing the helpdesk experience.

Celigo, NetSuite, and ShipBob are working seamlessly with our customer portal for post-purchase amendments.

🚀 Making an impact.

#Shopify
